{
  "mitigation_currently_implemented": "ICMP rate-limiting (per-echo-request) on the Ubuntu host and inline Snort protection in the path between the host and the network (snort-inline-1 between UbuntuComputer and Cisco switch). The rate-limiting is now targeted to ICMP Echo-Request to avoid affecting other ICMP types, and includes a drop policy for excess traffic beyond the limit. Edge QoS/edge device controls remain recommended but not yet actively configured in this run. This combination reduces the attacker’s ability to sustain a flood while the attacker remains in the network.",
  "comments": "Updated host-level mitigation to address previously identified gaps: (1) replaced a broad ICMP rate-limit with targeted ICMP Echo-Request rate limiting and explicit drop for excess traffic, (2) retained inline Snort protection to detect/drop flood-pattern traffic as it traverses the path, (3) no changes were made to the Snort device configuration (per constraints), (4) edge devices (FortiGate) configuration should be validated separately in a controlled step. This approach aims to reduce flood effectiveness while enabling validation via re-run of the attack using the same vectors. The topology previously inserted Snort inline to monitor and block floods; this remains active and in-path.",
  "device_identifier": "UbuntuComputer",
  "commands": [
    "iptables -A OUTPUT -p icmp --icmp-type echo-request -m limit --limit 10/second --limit-burst 20 -j ACCEPT",
    "iptables -A OUTPUT -p icmp --icmp-type echo-request -j DROP",
    "iptables -L OUTPUT -n -v"
  ]
}
